Predictive Modeling of Heart Disease using Logistic Regression, Neural Networks, Decision Trees, and bagging Algorithms with ROC Analysis

Steven Raimondo

26-Oct-2024


1 Introduction

1.1 Background

Cardiovascular Disease (CVD) is the leading cause of mortality in the USA, making it essential not only to diagnosis CVD at the early stages but now with advanced computing, data collection, and statistical techniques to predict what individuals are at high risk. This analysis leverages a comprehensive dataset comprised of not only standard clinical lab values such as cholesterol, fasting blood sugar, and blood pressure, but also clinical measurement data was obtained such as exercise induced angina, electrocardiogram (ECG) readout data, and chest pain type. The combination of both lab and clinical measurements makes this dataset very comprehensive in key potential predictive variables of CVD.

This analysis was performed by implementing several predictive modelling techniques such as logistic regression, a neural network (Perceptron), decision trees, and a bagging algorithm. Subsequent Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve analysis was performed for evaluation and determination of each methods predictive modelling to determine the optimal model for prediction of CVD.

1.1.1 Questions to be Addressed

What statistical technique best models the dataset in question to give us a prediction of whether an individual has CVD?

What variables are significant and how their relationships affect helping to predict which patients are at risk for CVD?

1.2 Working Data Set

The Heart dataset consists of 918 observations and 12 variables made up of both categorical and numeric variables that was preprocessed to recode some of the labels to better visualize the data and graphical outputs in the subsequent analysis.The dataset is comprised of both clinical lab variables and clinical measurement data derived from patients. The binary response variable in this dataset will be labelled ‘HeartDisease’ depicting whether that patient has heart disease or not. While the origin of the dataset is not known, it was deemed not necessary for this analysis as there was a comprehensive description of the variables provided on the data science community website called Kaggle. The following list includes the variable names, descriptions, type of variable, and outputs:

‘Age’: Patient’s age in years (Integer)

‘Sex’: Patient’s sex - Male or Female (Categorical)

‘ChestPainType’: Patient’s chest pain type - TA: Typical Angina, ATA: Atypical Angina, NAP: Non-Anginal Pain, ASY: Asymptomatic (Categorical)

‘RestingBP’: Resting blood pressure (mm Hg) (Integer)

‘Cholesterol’: Serum cholesterol reading (mm/dl) (Integer)

‘FastingBS’: Fasting blood glucose reading (> 120 mg/dl / <= 120 mg/dl) (Categorical)

‘RestingECG’: Resting ECG results (Normal: normal, ST: with ST-T wave abnormality, LVH: showing probable or definite left ventricular hypertrophy by Estes criteria) (Categorical)

‘MaxHR’: Maximum heart rate patient reached (Integer)

‘ExerciseAngina’: Exercise-induced angina (Yes or No) (Categorical)

‘Oldpeak’: old peak = ST (Numerical value measured in depression) (Numeric)

‘ST_Slope’: Slope of the peak exercise ST segment (Up, Flat, or Down) (Categorical)

‘HeartDisease’: (No or Yes) (Categorical)

An explanation for some of the not common variables was determined to be beneficial for readers of this analysis who are not familiar with some of the clinical meaning of the variables. Additionally, since there was no distinction made for how the restingbp was created, whether it was a combination of systolic and diastolic readings or simply one or the other and recorded as restingbp we will not make assumptions and simply refer to the variable as restingbp.

ChestPainType - Angina is short for Angina pectoris which is chest pain or discomfort due to coronary heart disease. Typical angina is pain that is substernal, jaw, and/or arm pressure-like pain which consistently occurs with exertion and consistently resolves within 15 minutes of rest and/or use of nitroglycerin(Cheng VY, Berman DS, Rozanski A, et al.). Atypical angina has is which patients present with nonanginal chest pain but are still symptomatic of cardiac ischemia issues. Non-Anginal Pain are patients that present chest pain but are not due to angina (cardio heart diseases). The chest pain could be due to gastrointestinal or muscoskeletal issues. Asymptomatic patients present with no chest pain.

FastingBS - While a fasting blood glucose reading of >125 mg/dl is defined by the Mayo Clinic as diabetic (Prediabetes - Diagnosis and treatment - Mayo Clinic. (n.d.)). Sutter Health defines it has > 120 mg/dl (Elevated blood sugar levels and diabetes | Sutter Health. (n.d.)). Therefore, we will use Sutter Health’s definition as our dataset has FastingBS as a binary variable without actual blood sugar values.

Oldpeak - Is a measurement of the ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest (Al Ahdal A, Rakhra M, Rajendran RR, et al.).

ST_Slope - The ST segment of the electrocardiogram (ECG) is the segment between the end of ventricular depolarization and beginning of ventricular repolarization on the ECG. Another way to put it is the ST segment represents the time from the myocardium maintains contraction to expel blood from the ventricles. The corresponding slope of the ST segment on the ECG can be either upward, flat, or downsloping. An upsloping ST segment is generally considered normal, while an ST slope which is horizontal is more characteristic of myocardial ischemia. Lastly, a downsloped is the worst prognosis and has been associated with cvd (Kashou AH, Basit H, Malik A. ST Segment). Therefore, being able to determine the different ST-slope a patient has on an ECG can help assist in identifying possible CVD.

2 Methodology

2.1 Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is a statistical technique used for modeling the probability of a binary outcome. We’ll use this technique in the subsequent analysis to assess the impact of various variables such as: Age, Sex, ST_Slope, RestingECG, and etc. on the likelihood of having cardiovascular disease represented by our dependent variable HeartDisease.

The logistic regression model allows us to estimate the odds of an outcome occuring via the logistic function in R by way of converting a linear relationship into a probability. The probability of this event allows us to predict, in this case whether a person will have HeartDisease or not.

The structural form of a logistic regression model is given by:

\(logit(p) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \beta_2 X_2 +\beta_kX_k\).

These components of logistic regression consist of:

  • \(logit(p)\) is the log-odds of the probability of an event occurring.
  • \(\beta_0\) denotes the Y-intercept when \(X\) is zero.
  • \(\beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_k\) are the coefficients associated with the explanatory variables
  • \(X_1, X_2, X_k\) are the explanatory variables

2.2 Single Layer Neural Network - Perceptron

The next statistical method employed in this comprehensive analysis involved the use of a single layer neural network - perceptron. This simple neural network is a supervised learning binary classification algorithm meant to mimic how a human brain processes information and is the simplest form of neural networks (Ezukwoke, K. 2019). Single layer Perceptron is very similar to logistic regression in that both give binary classifications outputs however has the ability to be extended into more complex multi-layer neural networks.The major elements of the single-layer perceptron involves the following:

Input Layer: Consists of one or more input neurons, that receives signals from external data.

Weights: Each input neuron has a corresponding weight, which helps represent the strength of the association between the input neuron and output neuron.

Bias: Added to the input layer to provide additional flexibility in modeling complex patterns

Activation Function: Determines the output of the perceptron based on the weighted sum of the inputs, threshold, and the bias term.

Output: A binary value, typically 0 or 1, which indicates what category the input data belongs to based on the threshold held by the activation function.

2.3 Decision Trees

A series of decision trees were used to implement machine learning algorithms that make decisions based on the value of the input features. Decision trees are a highly popular non parametric supervised learning statistically technique that is conceptually easily understood and visually self-explanatory statistical process to help answer yes and no decisions by way of nodes. They are highly versatile in that they can handle both categorical and continuous variables and are very efficient in breaking down the step by step process to a desired result by ways of splitting. However, due to the fact they are highly adaptable to fit any scenario and make it a split in the tree one must be careful as they are susceptible to over fitting if not mindful. We implemented two methods of splitting known as the Gini Index and Entropy. The Gini Index and Entropy are both measures of impurity where the Gini Index looks at the probability of being misclassified and chooses the smallest value for the split, whereas Entropy is based on information gained determining whether a split is worthwhile.

2.4 Bootstrap Method

The last statistical technique that was utilized in this analysis was that of an aggregated Bootstrap Method aka bagging. The Bootstrap Method is a powerful resampling technique that takes the original dataset and draws numerous samples from it allowing for replacement of observations. This is a relatively new but albeit very popular non-parametric method to deal with data where the underlying distribution is not known proposed by Efron in 1979 (B.Efron, 1979). The aggregated bagging technique is an ensemble machine learning process for this analysis takes the bootstrap samples (this analysis used 1000 samples) and subsequent predictions via logistic regression and assigns the final prediction. The combination of all these statistical techniques makes for a powerful model that can help reduce the variance in the data while also analyzing the most signficant explanatory variables of HeartDisease.

3.2.1 Data Manipulation

1 & 172 observations of RestingBP and cholesterol were noted to have 0 values recorded for both. The decision was made to impute this values as to not eliminate what would be nearly 30% of the dataset. The Multivariate Imputation by Chained Equations (MICE) method was utilized by way of Predictive Mean Matching method (PMM) to impute the missing values for RestingBP and Cholesterol. Conditional multiple imputation follows an iterative procedure, which models the conditional distribution of a certain variable given the distribution of other variables. The technique allows for flexibility as a distribution is assumed for each variable rather than the whole dataset (Getting Started with Multiple Imputation in R, n.d). The code chunk was hidden using the echo=FALSE option as the MICE does not suprress the output even with the results=FALSE option.

We can see below, as a result of MICE, we no longer have any 0 values for the variables RestingBP and Cholesterol.

sum(Heart$RestingBP == 0)
[1] 0
sum(Heart$Cholesterol == 0)
[1] 0

4 Statistical Modeling

4.1 Logistic Regression Modeling

Our first formal prediction modelling was done via logistic regression which is a statistical method used for modeling a binary outcome. We used our response variable of HeartDisease which states whether an individuals has the presence of HeartDisease coded as (1 - Yes, 0 - No). The model utilizes the other variables in the dataset as predictor variables that will help predict the probability of an individual with certain predictor variable characteristics and determine the probability based on a predetermined threshold (usually 0.5) that a person will have heart disease or not and will be assigned one of the output values previously mentioned.

Below we fit the reduced and full models, with the results hidden as to not take up an inordinate amount of space with interim models. The reduced model has variables chosen of particular interest. The variables Age, Sex, MaxHR, Cholesterol, and RestingBP were chosen due to the fact these are easily obtained measurements either via a simple physical exam and CompleteBloodCount (CBC). The reduced model showed that the RestingBP was insignificant at the 0.05 level with a p-value of 0.202390. The remaining variables were deemed to be statistically significant. The full model was able to provide some additional insights into the significance of the explanatory variables showing that Age, RestingBP, MaxHR, and RestingECG were all shown to be statistically insigifant at the 0.05 level.

library(MASS)
reducedModel <- glm(HeartDisease ~ Age + Sex + MaxHR + Cholesterol + RestingBP, 
family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = Heart)
summary(reducedModel)

fullModel <- glm(HeartDisease ~ ., 
family = binomial(link = "logit"),data = Heart)
summary(fullModel)

Stepwise selection Modeling is a powerful tool that allows R to add/remove a variable at each step in the process while at the same time evaluating the significance of the variables in the model with each addition/removal and adjusting as needed. We see the read out of the stepwise model that while there were a couple variables kept in the model even though they were deemed to be insignificant. The reason behind this could be due to the fact that there is some interaction/relationship of these variables with other signficaint variables in the model and thus removing them would also alter the model in a significant way.

stepwiseModel <- step(glm(HeartDisease ~ ., family = binomial(link = "logit"), data = Heart),
direction = "both", trace = 0)
summary(stepwiseModel)

4.3 Supervised Machine Learning Algorithms (Decision Trees)

The next step in our analysis was done utilizing a series of decision trees which we introduced in the introduction. However, we first needed to implement a random split approach to the Heart dataset, splitting into 2 separate datasets which can be seen in the below code chunk. One of the newly created datasets will be our training dataset appropriately named: traningData where we have 70% of our observations to train our model in subsequent code. The other dataset aptly named: testData holds 30% of the observations to test our model in later sections. By implementing the replace=FALSE, we do not have any duplicate observations in the split datasets.

library(caret)

set.seed(123)

n = dim(Heart)[1]
train.id = sample(1:n, round(0.7 * n), replace = FALSE)
trainData = Heart[train.id, ]
testData = Heart[-train.id, ]

Next we used the tree.builder function along with rpart to help us build our subsequent decision trees more conveniently. Some notes on the code below, is we’re using HeartDisease as our response variable still, and we removed any missing outcomes. We used a classification form factor along with specifying the minimum number of observations before splitting a node and minimum number of observations in the terminal nodes being 10. We also set the cp: complexity parameter to 0.01. The complexity parameter helps prune the tree and helps prevent over fitting by removing additional branches that mmight not be deemed significant. Lastly, to ensure the model’s complexity, we performed xval: a 10-fold cross validation.

library(rpart)

tree.builder <- function(in.data, fp, fn, purity) {
  tree = rpart(HeartDisease ~ .,
               data = in.data,
               na.action = na.rpart,
               method = "class",
               model = FALSE,
               x = FALSE,  
               y = TRUE,                    
               parms = list(                
                         loss = matrix(c(0, fp, fn, 0), ncol = 2, byrow = TRUE),
                         split = purity),     
               control = rpart.control(     
                       minsplit = 10,          
                       minbucket = 10,         
                       cp = 0.01,            
                       xval = 10               
               ))
  return(tree)}

We now use our function to define the six different decision tree models with the 1st 2 (Gini Index: non-penalization & entropy: non-penalization) plotted side by side for a better visualization

Model 1: gini.tree.11 utilizes the Gini index when making the decision for splitting. This model does not penalize for false positives or false negatives.

Model 2: info.tree.11 utilizes entropy when making the decision for splitting. This model does not penalize for false positives or false negatives.

Model 3: gini.tree.110 utilizes the Gini index when making the decision for splitting. This model penalizes a false negative 10x that of a false positive.

Model 4: info.tree.110 utilizes entropy when making the decision for splitting. This model penalizes a false negative 10x that of a false positive.

Model 5: gini.tree.101 utilizes the Gini index when making the decision for splitting. This model penalizes a false positive 10x that of a false negative.

Model 6: info.tree.101 utilizes entropy when making the decision for splitting. This model penalizes a false positive 10x that of a false negative.

The tree diagrams of models the Gini Index and Entropy that doesn’t incorporate any penalization’s is plotted below. We can see both models are the same indicating no difference between using Gini Index and Entropy in this example. The variable ST_Slope is the 1st split indicating it is the best variable for splitting up the data. We see that if you do not have an ST_Slope of UP you have a 0.82 probability of having HeartDisease. We see that 58% of our dataset fall into this category. While on the otherhand if you do have an ST_Slope of UP you only have a 0.18 probability of having HeartDisease and 42% of our dataset fell into this category. Below that there are different variables depending on which branch of the tree an individual is on. We see that while ChestPainType is on both, it doesn’t necessarily mean they will be the same. Since our variable chestpain has different levels, we see the levels are different for what’s best for splitting depending on whether your on the ST_Slope UP Yes or No side. The terminal nodes on the left and right sides show us both the lowest probability of having HeartDisease and conversely the highest probability respectively. Suppose an individual has an ST_Slpe: UP and their ChestPain is due to ATA or NAP, they have a 0.06 probability of having HeartDisase and the prediction is No they don’t. On the other side of the tree we see that if you don’t have an ST_Slope of UP and have some other type of chestpain than TA, ATA, or NAP you are at a 0.91 probability for having HeartDisease. It’s worth noting that once an individual has an ST_Slope of UP, there is only 1 path an indivudal can follow to have a predicted response of No for HeartDisease.

SenSpe = function(in.data, fp, fn, purity) {
  cutoff = seq(0, 1, length = 20)
  
  model = tree.builder(in.data, fp, fn, purity)
  
  pred = predict(model, newdata = in.data, type = "prob")
  
  in.data$HeartDisease = factor(ifelse(in.data$HeartDisease == "Yes", 1, 0), levels = c(0, 1))
  
  senspe.mtx = matrix(0, ncol = length(cutoff), nrow = 2, byrow = FALSE)
  
  for (i in 1:length(cutoff)) {pred.out = ifelse(pred[, 2] >= cutoff[i], 1, 0)

    TP = sum(pred.out == 1 & in.data$HeartDisease == 1)
    TN = sum(pred.out == 0 & in.data$HeartDisease == 0)
    FP = sum(pred.out == 1 & in.data$HeartDisease == 0)
    FN = sum(pred.out == 0 & in.data$HeartDisease == 1)
    
    senspe.mtx[1, i] = TP / (TP + FN)
    senspe.mtx[2, i] = TN / (TN + FP)}

  category = factor(in.data$HeartDisease, levels = c(0, 1))
  
  prediction = pred[, 2]
  
  if (length(category) != length(prediction)) {stop("Length of response (target) and predictor (probabilities) do not match!")}

  ROCobj <- roc(category, prediction)
  AUC = auc(ROCobj)
  
  list(senspe.mtx = senspe.mtx, AUC = round(AUC, 3))}

We still had the task to determine the optimal cut off and we see that each tree has their own optimal cut-off, and even within a single tree there may be several cut-offs which is ok. The average of the multiple cut-offs is a good method to choose as a final cut-off.

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)

Optm.cutoff = function(in.data, fp, fn, purity){
  n0 = dim(in.data)[1] / 5      
  cutoff = seq(0, 1, length = 20)       
  
  accuracy.mtx = matrix(0, ncol = 20, nrow = 5)
  
  for (k in 1:5) {valid.id = ((k-1) * n0 + 1):(k * n0)
    valid.dat = in.data[valid.id, ]     
    train.dat = in.data[-valid.id, ]  
    
    tree.model = tree.builder(train.dat, fp, fn, purity)
    pred = predict(tree.model, newdata = valid.dat, type = "prob")[, 2]

    for (i in 1:20) {pc.1 = ifelse(pred > cutoff[i], "Yes", "No")
      
      a1 = mean(pc.1 == valid.dat$HeartDisease)
      accuracy.mtx[k, i] = a1}}
  avg.acc = apply(accuracy.mtx, 2, mean)
  
  n = length(avg.acc)
  idx = which(avg.acc == max(avg.acc))
  tick.label = as.character(round(cutoff, 2))
  
  plot(1:n, avg.acc, xlab = "Cut-off score", ylab = "Average accuracy", 
       ylim = c(min(avg.acc), 1), axes = FALSE,
       main = paste("5-fold CV Optimal Cut-off \n", purity, "(fp, fn) = (", fp, ",", fn, ")"),
       cex.main = 0.9, col.main = "navy")
  axis(1, at = 1:20, label = tick.label, las = 2)
  axis(2)
  
  points(idx, avg.acc[idx], pch = 19, col = "red")
  segments(idx, min(avg.acc), idx, avg.acc[idx], col = "red")
  text(idx, avg.acc[idx] + 0.03, as.character(round(avg.acc[idx], 4)), 
       col = "red", cex = 0.8)}

par(mfrow = c(3, 2))

4.4 Bootstrap Method

The last statistical technique that we implemented that was mentioned in the introduction was the Bootstrap Method. As previously noted, this is a method that assumes our dataset is representative of the population and the dataset is large enough such that the empirical distribution can approximate the true distribution. These assumptions allowed us to perform the technique which is resampling the data with replacement to allow us to estimate the true distribution.

4.4.1 Bootstrap Method for Assessing AUC in Logistic Regression

Below we used a new dataset heart_data and ran 1000 bootstrap samples to help assess the AUC for the logistic regression model predicting HeartDisase. The resulting histogram provides a good example of the distribution of the AUC values for the 1000 bootstrap samples.

heart_data <- Heart

heart_data$status = ifelse(heart_data$HeartDisease == "Yes", "yes", "no")

btAUC.vec = c()

B = 1000

sample.size = dim(heart_data)[1]

cut.off.seq = seq(0, 1, length = 100)

for (k in 1:B) {
  boot.id = sample(1:sample.size, sample.size, replace = TRUE)
  boot.sample = heart_data[boot.id, ]
  
  boot.logistic = glm(factor(status) ~ Age + Sex + ChestPainType + RestingBP + Cholesterol +
                        FastingBS + RestingECG + MaxHR + ExerciseAngina + Oldpeak + ST_Slope, 
                      family = binomial, data = boot.sample)
  
  pred.prob = predict.glm(boot.logistic, newdata = boot.sample, type = "response")
  
  sensitivity.vec = NULL
  specificity.vec = NULL
  
  for (i in 1:100) {
    pred.status = as.numeric(pred.prob > cut.off.seq[i])
    TN = sum(pred.status == 0 & boot.sample$status == "no")
    FN = sum(pred.status == 0 & boot.sample$status == "yes")
    FP = sum(pred.status == 1 & boot.sample$status == "no")
    TP = sum(pred.status == 1 & boot.sample$status == "yes")
    
    sensitivity.vec[i] = TP / (TP + FN)
    specificity.vec[i] = TN / (TN + FP)}

  one.minus.spec = 1 - specificity.vec
  sens.vec = sensitivity.vec
  
  prediction = pred.prob
  category = boot.sample$status == "yes"
  ROCobj <- roc(category, prediction)
  btAUC.vec[k] = round(auc(ROCobj), 4)}

hist(btAUC.vec, xlab = "Bootstrap AUC", main = "Bootstrap Sampling Distribution of AUCs \n (Heart Disease Prediction Model)")

The 95% bootstrap confidence interval of the AUC is defined to be 2.5% and 97.5% quantiles of the bootstrap AUCs which can be seen below via the pander function. The confidence interval of AUC can be useful for variable selection given if two confidence intervals of AUC overlapped. The predictive performances of the two corresponding predictive models are not significantly different. A simpler model would be recommended as a replacement

pander(quantile(btAUC.vec, c(0.025, 0.975)))

4.4.2 BAGGING - Classification Trees

We next used bagging for classification trees where we created 150 trees for the procedure using the Gini Index as our splitting method. We see the resulting AUC came out to be 0.936 with an optimal cut-off of 0.579. Lastly we see the accuracy of the model was 0.872

5 Conclusions

This comprehensive analysis took aim at predicting whether an individual has HeartDisease given certain given predictor variables. The EDA conducted revealed a great deal about the relationships amongst the variables. We saw the positive correlation between RestingBP and Age. We also saw the inverse correlation between MaxHR and Age where as a person gets older their MaxHR decreases. Additionally, with MaxHR as it increases, RestingBP decreases. It’s worth noting again that we saw none to negligible difference in our boxplots of cholesterol values stratifying on HeartDisease. Many more insights into the relationships could be examined with further analsysis and would certainly be a useful endeavor.

We performed 4 main types of analysis utilizing the logistic regression model, Perceptron, Decision Trees, and bagging bootstrap. Our final model in logistic regression demonstrated that the variables: Age, ST_Slope, FastingBS, ExerciseAngina, and OldPeak were highly statistically significant. We saw the importance of ST_Slope in the decision tree model, which was predicted given the background we received on the variables. We also found that the bagging bootstrap method yielded the highest AUC and accuracy at 0.936 and 0.872. While the bagging bootstrap was demed to be the best model in this analysis, we saw how each model’s flexibility and usefulness can be utilized in many different scenarios and datasets.

The development of ever advanced methods to capture data regarding a patients health can assist greatly in researchers determine which factors are significant in predicting HeartDisease and in some cases a warning could be utilized if necessary. The need however to capture accurate date remains a challenging area as many of the initial points of data gathering that are not necessarily being done for a clinical trial, often has a lot of errors and missing values. We must treat these dataset with skepticism but they can still provide valuable insights. Lastly, we’ve shown that there are numerous good methods to handle predictive modeling of both categorical and continuous datasets.
